Part 2 - RNA-seq analysis with DESeq2

2024-03-06

Introduction

The following script is based on the DESeq2 worflow, and consists on the analysis of RNA-seq data from the count matrix input.

Overview of RNA-seq

RNA sequencing (RNA-seq) measures the abundance of the transcription of each gene, quantifying gene expression.

Steps:

  1. RNA isolation
  2. Fragmentation (few hundred bases long)
  3. Library preparation (reverse-transcription and amplification)
  4. Sequencing (output reads)
  5. Alignment to reference genome (e.g., HISAT2)
  6. Quantification of reads per gene (e.g., featureCounts)
image from (https://mbernste.github.io/posts/rna_seq_basics/)

Construct the DESeqDataSet

library(DESeq2) #after installation

dds <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(countData = cts,
                              colData = coldata,
                              design = ~ Group)
## Warning in DESeqDataSet(se, design = design, ignoreRank): some variables in

Pre-filtering

The removal of rows (genes) with low count values is useful to reduce the memory requirements and increase the speed of count modelling. Here, we keep only the genes with at least 10 counts for a minimal of 3 samples

keep <- rowSums(counts(dds) >= 10) >= 3
dds <- dds[keep,]
dds
## class: DESeqDataSet 
## dim: 14714 6 
## metadata(1): version
## assays(1): counts

## rowData names(0):
## colnames(6): A1 A2 ... B2 B3
## colData names(4): Sample Group Age Sex

Differential expression analysis

The analysis is based on the Negative Binomial (a.k.a Gamma-Poisson) distribution. The DESeq function performs the estimation of size factors, estimation of dispersion and the Negative Binomial GLM fitting and Wald statistics. The results function extracts a results table with log2 fold changes, p values and adjusted p values.

dds <- DESeq(dds)
res <- results(dds, contrast = c("Group","B","A"))
res <- as.data.frame(res)
res$Gene <- rownames(res)
head(res)

Representation of the results

Volcano Plot

library(ggplot2)
library(ggrepel)

res$logadjp = - log10(res$padj)

ggplot(res, aes(x = log2FoldChange, y = logadjp))+ 
  geom_point(data = subset(res, padj < 0.05 & log2FoldChange > 0), 
             color = "#B44143")+
  geom_point(data = subset(res, padj < 0.05 & log2FoldChange < 0), 
             color = "#386641")+
  geom_point(data = subset(res, padj > 0.05), 
             color = "grey")+
  geom_point(data = subset(res,abs(log2FoldChange) < 0), 
             color = "grey")+
  geom_hline(yintercept = -log10(0.05), linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = c(0), linetype = "dashed") +
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(panel.grid = element_blank()) +
  xlab("Log2(Fold Change)") +
  ylab("-Log10 (Adj P)") +
  geom_text_repel(data = subset(res, abs(`log2FoldChange`) > 5 & padj < 0.05), aes(label=Gene), size = 2)
## Warning: ggrepel: 786 unlabeled data points (too many overlaps). Consider
## increasing max.overlaps

Plot the expression of individual genes

Select the most significant gene by padj (SCD).

plotCounts(dds=dds,gene = "SCD",intgroup = "Group")

norm_counts <- DESeq2::counts(dds, normalized=T)
norm_counts <- as.data.frame(norm_counts)

df<- as.matrix(norm_counts["SCD",])
df2 <- as.data.frame(t(df)) 
colnames(df2)<-"gene"
df3 <- cbind(df2,coldata)

ggplot(df3, aes(Group,gene, fill=Group)) + 
  geom_boxplot()+
  geom_dotplot(binaxis = "y", stackdir = "center")+
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("#3f858c","#731a12"))+
        scale_x_discrete(limits=c("A","B"))+
        labs(title="SCD", y = "normalized counts")+
        theme_bw()
## Bin width defaults to 1/30 of the range of the data. Pick better value with
## `binwidth`.
